{{subspeciesbox |image = Sand Mountain Blue Butterfly.jpg |image_alt = Euphilotes pallescens arenamontana |image_caption = ''Euphilotes pallescens arenamontana'' |status = T1 |status_system = TNC |status_ref = <ref name=NS>NatureServe. 2017. NatureServe Explorer: An online encyclopedia of life [web application]. Version 7.1. NatureServe, Arlington, Virginia. Available http://explorer.natureserve.org/servlet/NatureServe?sourceTemplate=tabular_report.wmt&loadTemplate=species_RptComprehensive.wmt&selectedReport=RptComprehensive.wmt&summaryView=tabular_report.wmt&elKey=121198&paging=home&save=true&startIndex=1&nextStartIndex=1&reset=false&offPageSelectedElKey=121198&offPageSelectedElType=species&offPageYesNo=true&post_processes=&radiobutton=radiobutton&selectedIndexes=121198 . (Accessed: September 27, 2017 ).</ref> |genus = Euphilotes |species = pallescens |subspecies = arenamontana |authority = [[George T. Austin|Austin]], 1998 }} [[File:Sand Mountain.jpg|thumb|[[Sand Mountain (Nevada)|Sand Mountain Recreation Area]]]]
The '''Sand Mountain blue''' (''Euphilotes pallescens arenamontana'') is a [[butterfly]] of the [[Lycaenidae|gossamer winged]] variety that is only found around the [[Sand Mountain (Nevada)|Sand Mountain Recreation Area]] near [[Fallon, Nevada]]. This species is one of several belonging to the [[Polyommatinae|"blue" subfamily]] of Lycaenidae.<ref name="fws">{{cite web|title=Sand Mountain Blue Butterfly|url=http://www.fws.gov/nevada/nv_species/smb_butterfly.html|publisher=Nevada Fish and Wildlife Office|accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref>
==Biological characteristics== These butterflies are known for their almost complete dependence upon [[Eriogonum nummulare|Kearney buckwheat]]; eating the fallen leaves of the plant as [[caterpillar|larvae]], and drinking the [[nectar]] of the flowers as adults - however, the adults occasionally feed on other plant species. Like many gossamer-winged butterflies, Sand Mountain blues have a close relationship with [[ant]]s; in this case, desert [[carpenter ant]]s feed on a [[sugar]]y secretion of the larvae; whether the larvae [[mutualism (biology)|also benefit]] or [[commensalism|not]] is yet to be determined. Once the larvae [[metamorphosis|metamorphose]] into the [[pupa]]l stage, rather than remaining fixed to buckwheat plant, the [[Pupa#Chrysalis|chrysalis]] drops into the [[plant litter|leaf litter]] at the base. Upon reaching adulthood, ''E. pallescens arenamontana'' typically measure anywhere between {{convert|10.0|mm|in|abbr=on}} and {{convert|11.9|mm|in|abbr=on}}. The species is not known to [[Lepidoptera migration|migrate]], and stays within {{convert|200|ft|m|abbr=on}} of its host plant. The lifespan of an adult Sand Mountain blue is approximately one week.<ref name="fws"/><ref name="petition">{{cite web|title=Petition to list the Sand Mountain Blue Butterfly as a Threatened or Endangered Species Under the U.S. Endangered Species Act|url=http://www.fws.gov/nevada/nv_species/documents/smbb/smbb_petition.pdf|format=PDF|author=[[Center for Biological Diversity]] |author2=[[Xerces Society]] |author3=[[Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility]] |author4=Nevada Outdoor Recreation Association |accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref>
==Status== The Sand Mountain blue species, ''[[Euphilotes pallescens|E. pallescens]]'' has been officially classified as being [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]], while the subspecies ''E. p. arenamontana'' has been labeled as critically imperiled, at great risk of extinction.<ref name=NS /> In 2004 a [[petition]] was filed to investigate the [[conservation status|status]] of the Sand Mountain blue and whether it should be placed on the [[endangered species|endangered]] or [[threatened species]] lists. Currently Sand Mountain blues are referred to as "[[rare species|rare]]" because of their small [[range (biology)|geographical distribution]] around the Sand Mountain [[dune]].<ref name="petition"/> In March 2007, several [[off-road vehicle]] trails were closed off in order to protect the species and its host plant from intrusion.<ref name="msnbc">{{cite web|title=Move to protect butterfly steps on off-roaders|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17722427|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=2007-03-24}}</ref>
